<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Experts Present Policy Recommendations for Obama Administration</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Jes Gagnon
		
		<span class="date">Nov. 13, 2008</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:freeman@mail.ucf.edu">Mark Freeman, Global Perspectives</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-0935</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.ucfglobalperspectives.org">UCF Global Perspectives Office</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Offering a timely response to the presidential election, experts across a range of fields gathered at UCF last week to discuss &ldquo;America&rsquo;s Next President and the World.&rdquo; Seven presenters from around the world spoke about global issues such as the international economy and terrorism, as well as regional concerns in Latin America and South and East Asia.</p>
<p>The morning keynote, delivered by Senior Fellow at the American Security Project Bernard Finel, laid out a framework for the challenges of the next administration. Addressing topics such as security, the economy and international development, Finel warned that the U.S. must reinvent its old Cold War policies and pacts to reflect the needs of a global society. More than that, the next administration must be clear in its commitments and present a singular face to the international community in order to reach new agreements. &ldquo;We need to reassure the world now. Greatness requires restraint, and leadership requires consensus.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Building from the morning keynote, other presenters spoke in detail about specific challenges that the next president&nbsp;will face.</p>
<p>Speaking on U.S. and Latin American relations, former ambassador to Colombia Myles Frechette stated that the interconnected economies of the two regions cannot be overlooked. While support for democracy may not abound in Latin American countries, the belief that liberal economic policy leads to stability and growth is strong. Frechette recommends that the U.S. capitalize on economic ties with the region, while supporting a shift from commodities to value-added exports to encourage development.</p>
<p>Lisa Curtis, senior research fellow at the Heritage Foundation, gave a comprehensive overview of challenges and opportunities in South Asia. Protracted conflict in Afghanistan and threats from radicals in Pakistan must be immediately addressed by the new administration. On a more positive note, India&rsquo;s role as a multi-ethnic democratic society makes it a strong leader for development in the region, as well as a strategic partner for the U.S.</p>
<p>UCF&rsquo;s own director of the Institute for Economic Competitiveness, Sean Snaith, focused his presentation on the global economy, particularly on the myth of decoupling and the importance of understanding financial linkages. Snaith said that while the U.S. is no longer the sole actor leading, &ldquo;it is now observed that the U.S. is inexorably tied to the pulse of the world economy.&rdquo; The next administration&rsquo;s fiscal and monetary policy must reflect restraint to avoid unintended global consequences.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Doug Inkley, senior scientist for the National Wildlife Federation, praised both presidential candidates for the firm attention to the problem of global climate change during their campaigns. For what is at stake, Inkley strongly urged that the next president work to secure a global commitment to reducing carbon emissions and operate within multilateral arrangements to reduce oil subsidies and encourage the use of alternative energy sources.</p>
<p>In a somber but inspiring lecture to the conference, Beatrice Fernando, an associate with the American Anti-Slavery Group, told her personal story of forced captivity and servitude in Lebanon. After narrowly escaping death to flee from her captor, she found that the emotional affliction and social stigma once she returned home to Sri Lanka were also tough battles themselves. Fernando is an advocate for the rights and humane treatment of trafficking victims, which she considers just as important as working to counter human trafficking at home and abroad.</p>
<p>Mike Chinoy, a former foreign correspondent for CNN, delivered the luncheon keynote on challenges in East Asia. Issues coming from South Korea, North Korea and Japan, while important, pale in comparison to the tensions between the U.S. and China, he said. Economic, security, environmental and political problems exist within what Chinoy recognizes to be America&rsquo;s most important bilateral relationship. Because strategic engagement is often hampered between the two hegemons, initiatives addressing global health and climate change are strong foundations for cooperation.</p>
<p>More than 200 people attended the conference and benefited from the experts&rsquo; policy recommendations for the greatest challenges facing America&rsquo;s next president. In addition to the Global Perspectives Office, the event was sponsored by the National Conference of Editorial Writers, the Global Connections Foundation, Lawrence J. Chastang and the Chastang Foundation, Anil and Chitre Deshpande, and C.T. Hsu and Associates.&nbsp;</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity:</strong> The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th largest in the nation with more than 50,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
